{
  "query": "What are the conservation benefits of prohibiting spearfishing in marine reserves in the Mediterranean?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from multiple studies demonstrates significant conservation benefits from prohibiting spearfishing in Mediterranean marine reserves. Two studies in the Mediterranean (France, Corsica) found that prohibiting spearfishing increased the abundances of European seabass and gilthead seabream compared to fished areas after two to seven years. These protected areas also resulted in larger fish sizes for European seabass compared to protected and unprotected fished areas. A replicated site comparison study in the Mediterranean found that prohibiting spearfishing in specific zones of a marine reserve resulted in higher commercial and recreational fishery catches of targeted common dentex compared to zones that allowed spearfishing and areas outside the reserve after one to three years. Marine protected areas prohibiting all fishing (which includes spearfishing) in the Mediterranean showed higher fish species richness compared to fished areas, increased abundances and/or biomasses of fish, and larger fish overall after periods of protection ranging from one to 25 years.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2672",
    "2224",
    "2682"
  ]
}

