tools_called.args:
{"query": "What are the effects on marine fish populations of prohibiting different types of bottom fishing gear?", "summary": "Studies examining the prohibition of different types of bottom fishing gear show varied effects on marine fish populations. Prohibiting all mobile and static fishing gears that catch bottom (demersal) species (Action 2654) showed mixed results: one study found higher numbers of larger and older cod after 15 years of closure, while another found no effect on fish densities after 2-7 years. Fish densities varied between species and were influenced by depth and temperature. Cod showed better growth in closed areas after 5-15 years compared to openly fished areas.

Prohibiting mobile fishing gears dragged across the seafloor (Action 2673) demonstrated more consistent positive effects across 10 studies. These included higher total fish biomass after 15 years, increased adult red mullet biomass after 14 years, improved recruitment of young red mullet, and larger sizes of adult red mullet. However, effects varied between individual fish groups and with habitat type. One study showed increased catch rates after 3-6 years of prohibiting beach and seine nets.

Prohibiting shellfish dredging (Action 2668) showed no effect on bottom-dwelling fish abundance or species richness after 10 years of closure. Designated Marine Protected Areas that prohibit all towed fishing gear (Actions 2229, 2102) showed positive effects on invertebrate populations rather than fish, including greater invertebrate abundance and biomass, more scallops, and higher proportions of older, larger scallops compared to fished areas.", "action_ids": ["2654", "2673", "2668", "2229", "2102"]}

