{
  "query": "How do the effects of prohibiting all commercial fishing on fish abundance vary across different ocean basins?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from action documents, the effects of prohibiting commercial fishing on fish abundance vary considerably across different ocean basins. In the Atlantic Ocean/Gulf of Mexico, studies showed mixed results with some commercially targeted species showing higher abundance after protection while others showed no change. The Mediterranean Sea demonstrated varied responses with some species groups showing higher abundance after five years while others like white seabream showed no biomass increase. The Indian Ocean showed mixed effects with some fish groups having higher abundance and larger overall fish size in protected areas. The Tasman Sea region was notable for showing mostly decreased abundance or mixed results after fishing prohibition. The South China Sea showed conflicting results with decreased species richness but increased overall fish density in the wider region. The South Atlantic Ocean showed no significant differences in species composition or diversity after 40 years of protection. These findings demonstrate that fish abundance responses to commercial fishing prohibition are highly variable between ocean basins, with no consistent global pattern of positive or negative effects.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2667",
    "2682"
  ]
}

