  "relevant_summary": "Documented ecological outcomes of managing small-scale traditional fisheries show mixed results. One study in the Adriatic Sea (Italy) found that a marine protected area zone allowing only artisanal fishing activity for three years had higher overall commercial catch rates of five of seven species compared to unprotected areas openly fished (Action 2678). In contrast, a study of prohibiting customary fishing in Papua New Guinea showed limited ecological benefits, with only one of seven fish species showing higher abundance after eight years of closure, though six of seven species showed lower flight response distance, potentially making them more vulnerable to spear gun capture (Action 2675). Community-based fisheries management in New Zealand showed positive outcomes for scallop populations, with customary fisheries areas having more New Zealand scallops compared to fully protected areas or areas allowing recreational harvest, though scallops tended to be smaller (Action 2242).",
